    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Anguish at Gracie Mansion</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Chris Laurence letter on May 11 article says Mayor Rudolph Giuliani should do himself and New York a favor and withdraw from Senate race</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>There are many qualified people whose personal lives are stable. In the next few months Mayor Rudolph W.  Giuliani must deal with marital separation (front page, May 11). Having seen people go through this process, I think it is in his interests to keep it private. Inevitably, work suffers; the mind is preoccupied. This is hardly the condition for a Senate candidate.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>There are many qualified people whose personal lives are stable. In the next few months Mayor Rudolph W.  Giuliani must deal with marital separation (front page, May 11). Having seen people go through this process, I think it is in his interests to keep it private. Inevitably, work suffers; the mind is preoccupied. This is hardly the condition for a Senate candidate.</p>
        <p>Add to this Mr. Giuliani's prostate cancer, and I think he could use some time to regroup. The personal scenario is quite distressing and not conducive to the battle royal of a Senate campaign. Mr. Giuliani should do himself and New York a favor and withdraw from the race.</p>
        <p>CHRIS LAURENCE  Thousand Oaks, Calif., May 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
